<!-- NEURAL NETWORKS -->
<section class="section" id="nn">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div class="sec-icon si-gold">🧠</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <div class="sec-tag">Chapter 4.1</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Neural Networks — From Perceptron to Deep Nets</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-gold">
    <div class="card-title ct-gold">The Problem: Why Do We Need Neural Networks?</div>
    <p>Traditional programming says: <em>"Write rules explicitly."</em> But for tasks like recognizing handwriting, translating languages, or generating text — the rules are impossibly complex. Neural networks <strong>learn rules from data</strong>.</p>
    <p>🧠 <em>Analogy:</em> Instead of programming a rule book for "what a cat looks like", you show a neural network 1 million cat photos. It figures out the rules itself.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="g2">
    <div class="card card-cyan">
      <div class="card-title ct-cyan">The Perceptron (1957)</div>
      <p>The very first "neuron". Takes inputs, multiplies by weights, sums them, passes through an activation function.</p>
      <p><strong>One neuron = one decision boundary (a straight line)</strong>. Cannot solve XOR — the first "AI winter" cause.</p>
      <div class="code"><span class="cm"># Single Perceptron</span>
output = <span class="fn">activation</span>(w1*x1 + w2*x2 + bias)
<span class="cm"># If output > threshold → class 1 else class 0</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-violet">
      <div class="card-title ct-violet">Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)</div>
      <p>Stack multiple layers of neurons. Each layer transforms the data. Now we can solve any problem — the <strong>Universal Approximation Theorem</strong> guarantees this.</p>
      <p>Input Layer → Hidden Layer(s) → Output Layer</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="flow">
    <div class="flow-box active"><div class="flow-label">Input Layer</div><div class="flow-text">Raw Features</div><div class="flow-sub">x₁, x₂, x₃ … xₙ</div></div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
    <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">Hidden Layer 1</div><div class="flow-text">Learned Representations</div><div class="flow-sub">Linear + Activation</div></div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
    <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">Hidden Layer 2</div><div class="flow-text">Higher-Level Features</div><div class="flow-sub">Edges → Shapes → Objects</div></div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
    <div class="flow-box highlight"><div class="flow-label">Output Layer</div><div class="flow-text">Prediction</div><div class="flow-sub">Class / Value / Probability</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-gold" style="margin-top:16px">
    <div class="card-title ct-gold">Activation Functions — Why They Matter</div>
    <p>Without activation functions, stacking layers is useless — the whole network collapses to just one linear equation. Activations add <strong>non-linearity</strong>, letting networks learn complex patterns.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="tw">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>Formula</th><th>Output Range</th><th>Best Used For</th><th>Problem</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="hl">Sigmoid</td><td><span class="tag tc">1/(1+e⁻ˣ)</span></td><td>(0, 1)</td><td>Binary classification output</td><td>Vanishing gradients in deep nets</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Tanh</td><td><span class="tag tv">2σ(2x)−1</span></td><td>(−1, 1)</td><td>Hidden layers (old style)</td><td>Still vanishing gradient</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">ReLU ★</td><td><span class="tag tg">max(0, x)</span></td><td>[0, ∞)</td><td>Most hidden layers today</td><td>Dying ReLU (neg inputs → 0 forever)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Leaky ReLU</td><td><span class="tag tl">max(0.01x, x)</span></td><td>(−∞, ∞)</td><td>Fix dying ReLU</td><td>Adds hyperparameter α</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">GELU ★★</td><td><span class="tag tg">x·Φ(x)</span></td><td>(−∞, ∞)</td><td>Transformers, BERT, GPT</td><td>Slightly slower to compute</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">Softmax</td><td><span class="tag tc">eˣⁱ/Σeˣʲ</span></td><td>(0,1) sums to 1</td><td>Multi-class classification output</td><td>Only for output, not hidden layers</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-cyan">
    <div class="card-title ct-cyan">Forward Propagation — The Prediction Step</div>
    <p>Data flows forward through the network, layer by layer. At each layer: multiply inputs by weights, add bias, apply activation. Final layer produces the prediction.</p>
    <div class="code"><span class="cm"># PyTorch — Forward Pass</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> torch
<span class="kw">import</span> torch.nn <span class="kw">as</span> nn

<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="cls">MLP</span>(nn.Module):
    <span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">__init__</span>(<span class="hl">self</span>):
        <span class="fn">super</span>().<span class="fn">__init__</span>()
        <span class="hl">self</span>.layers = nn.<span class="fn">Sequential</span>(
            nn.<span class="fn">Linear</span>(<span class="num">784</span>, <span class="num">256</span>),   <span class="cm"># Input → Hidden</span>
            nn.<span class="fn">ReLU</span>(),
            nn.<span class="fn">Linear</span>(<span class="num">256</span>, <span class="num">128</span>),   <span class="cm"># Hidden → Hidden</span>
            nn.<span class="fn">ReLU</span>(),
            nn.<span class="fn">Linear</span>(<span class="num">128</span>, <span class="num">10</span>)    <span class="cm"># Hidden → Output (10 classes)</span>
        )
    <span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">forward</span>(<span class="hl">self</span>, x):
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="hl">self</span>.layers(x)</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-violet">
    <div class="card-title ct-violet">Backpropagation — How Networks Learn</div>
    <p>After a forward pass, we calculate how wrong the prediction was (the <strong>loss</strong>). Backpropagation computes <strong>how much each weight contributed to the error</strong> using the chain rule of calculus. Then we update weights to reduce the error.</p>
    <p>🎯 <em>Analogy:</em> Like a chef tasting soup and tracing back which ingredient made it too salty — then adjusting the recipe accordingly.</p>
    <div class="milestone">
      <div class="ms-box"><div class="ms-n">Step 1</div><div class="ms-t">Forward Pass</div><div class="ms-d">Get prediction</div></div>
      <div class="ms-box"><div class="ms-n">Step 2</div><div class="ms-t">Compute Loss</div><div class="ms-d">How wrong?</div></div>
      <div class="ms-box"><div class="ms-n">Step 3</div><div class="ms-t">Backprop</div><div class="ms-d">∂Loss/∂weights</div></div>
      <div class="ms-box"><div class="ms-n">Step 4</div><div class="ms-t">Update Weights</div><div class="ms-d">w = w - lr·∇</div></div>
      <div class="ms-box"><div class="ms-n">Repeat</div><div class="ms-t">Train Loop</div><div class="ms-d">Until converged</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g3">
    <div class="card card-gold">
      <div class="card-title ct-gold">Loss Functions</div>
      <ul class="bl">
        <li><strong>MSE</strong> — Regression tasks (predict numbers)</li>
        <li><strong>Cross-Entropy</strong> — Classification (predict class)</li>
        <li><strong>BCE</strong> — Binary classification</li>
        <li><strong>Huber Loss</strong> — Robust to outliers</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-cyan">
      <div class="card-title ct-cyan">Optimizers</div>
      <ul class="bl cyan">
        <li><strong>SGD</strong> — Classic, needs tuning</li>
        <li><strong>Momentum</strong> — Faster convergence</li>
        <li><strong>Adam ★</strong> — Adaptive, industry default</li>
        <li><strong>AdamW</strong> — Adam + weight decay</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-violet">
      <div class="card-title ct-violet">Regularization</div>
      <ul class="bl violet">
        <li><strong>Dropout</strong> — Randomly zero neurons (0.1–0.5)</li>
        <li><strong>Batch Norm</strong> — Normalize layer activations</li>
        <li><strong>L1/L2</strong> — Weight penalties</li>
        <li><strong>Early Stopping</strong> — Stop when val loss rises</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula">
    <div class="formula-top"><span class="formula-name">Gradient Descent Update Rule</span><span class="formula-badge">Core of all learning</span></div>
    <div class="formula-eq">θ = θ − α · ∇ₒL(θ)</div>
    <div class="formula-desc">θ = all weights and biases · α = learning rate (how big a step to take) · ∇ₒL(θ) = gradient (direction of steepest increase in loss, so we go opposite)</div>
    <div class="formula-note"><strong style="color:var(--gold)">Intuition:</strong> Walking downhill in a foggy mountain. You can only see which direction is downhill right now, and you take a small step that direction. Repeat until you reach the valley (minimum loss).</div>
  </div>

  <div class="g2">
    <div class="card card-rose">
      <div class="card-title ct-rose">Batch Normalization</div>
      <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Each layer's inputs shift as previous weights update — making training unstable and slow (Internal Covariate Shift).</p>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Normalize each mini-batch to have mean=0, variance=1, then scale and shift with learned parameters γ and β.</p>
      <p><em>Effect:</em> Allows higher learning rates, faster convergence, acts as mild regularizer.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-lime">
      <div class="card-title ct-lime">Dropout</div>
      <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Networks overfit — memorize training data instead of learning generalizable patterns.</p>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Randomly set p% of neurons to 0 during each training forward pass. Forces the network to learn redundant representations.</p>
      <p><em>Effect:</em> Trains an ensemble of ~2ⁿ sub-networks simultaneously.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CNN -->
<section class="section" id="cnn">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div class="sec-icon si-cyan">👁️</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <div class="sec-tag">Chapter 4.2</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN)</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-cyan">
    <div class="card-title ct-cyan">The Problem CNNs Solve</div>
    <p>A 224×224 pixel image has 150,528 pixels × 3 colors = 451,584 inputs. With a 1000-neuron hidden layer, that's 451 million weights — just for layer 1. Impossible to train and no spatial awareness.</p>
    <p>🔍 <em>CNNs exploit the fact that nearby pixels are correlated.</em> Instead of connecting every pixel to every neuron, small filters slide across the image looking for local patterns.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="flow">
    <div style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:8px;font-family:var(--fm);font-size:10px;color:var(--text3);text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px">CNN Architecture Flow</div>
    <div class="flow-row">
      <div class="flow-box active"><div class="flow-label">Input</div><div class="flow-text">224×224×3</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">Conv Layer</div><div class="flow-text">Filters/Kernels</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">Activation</div><div class="flow-text">ReLU</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">Pooling</div><div class="flow-text">Downsample</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box highlight"><div class="flow-label">Repeat N×</div><div class="flow-text">Feature Maps</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
    <div class="flow-row">
      <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">Flatten</div><div class="flow-text">Vector</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box active"><div class="flow-label">Fully Connected</div><div class="flow-text">MLP Layers</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box violet"><div class="flow-label">Softmax</div><div class="flow-text">Class Probabilities</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g2">
    <div class="card card-gold">
      <div class="card-title ct-gold">Convolution — The Core Operation</div>
      <p>A small matrix (kernel/filter, e.g. 3×3) slides across the image, computing the dot product at each position. This detects one specific pattern everywhere in the image.</p>
      <p>🎯 A 3×3 edge-detection filter applied to a 224×224 image produces a 222×222 "feature map" showing where that edge pattern exists.</p>
      <p><strong>Padding:</strong> Add zeros around border to keep output same size<br><strong>Stride:</strong> How many pixels to move the filter each step</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-violet">
      <div class="card-title ct-violet">Feature Maps — Hierarchical Learning</div>
      <ul class="bl violet">
        <li><strong>Layer 1:</strong> Edges, colors, basic textures (horizontal/vertical lines)</li>
        <li><strong>Layer 2:</strong> Corners, curves, basic shapes (circles, squares)</li>
        <li><strong>Layer 3:</strong> Complex patterns (eyes, wheels, feathers)</li>
        <li><strong>Layer N:</strong> Full object recognition ("cat", "car", "face")</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="tw">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Architecture</th><th>Year</th><th>Key Innovation</th><th>Depth</th><th>Impact</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="hl">LeNet-5</td><td>1998</td><td>First successful CNN — digit recognition</td><td>5 layers</td><td>MNIST benchmark</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">AlexNet</td><td>2012</td><td>GPU training, ReLU, Dropout</td><td>8 layers</td><td>Started deep learning era</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">VGG-16</td><td>2014</td><td>Very deep 3×3 filters only</td><td>16 layers</td><td>Transfer learning baseline</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl" style="color:var(--gold)">ResNet ★</td><td>2015</td><td>Residual connections — skip connections</td><td>50–152 layers</td><td>Solved vanishing gradients</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="hl">EfficientNet ★</td><td>2019</td><td>Compound scaling (width+depth+resolution)</td><td>Scalable</td><td>Best accuracy/efficiency</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-rose">
    <div class="card-title ct-rose">ResNet — The Vanishing Gradient Solution</div>
    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Very deep networks stopped learning because gradients became vanishingly small before reaching early layers.</p>
    <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Skip connections (residual connections) that bypass layers: <code style="font-family:var(--fm);color:var(--cyan)">output = F(x) + x</code></p>
    <p>🔌 <em>Analogy:</em> Adding a highway bypass through a city — even if the city roads are congested, traffic can still flow. Gradients can always flow directly through skip connections, no matter how deep the network.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- RNN -->
<section class="section" id="rnn">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div class="sec-icon si-violet">🔄</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <div class="sec-tag">Chapter 4.3</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">RNN / LSTM / GRU — Sequential Learning</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-violet">
    <div class="card-title ct-violet">The Problem: Processing Sequences</div>
    <p>MLPs and CNNs have fixed-size inputs. But language is a sequence of variable length. The meaning of "bank" depends on context: "river bank" vs "money bank". We need memory across time steps.</p>
    <p>🎭 <em>Analogy:</em> Reading a book. You understand each word in context of everything you've read so far. A neural network needs the same sequential memory.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="flow">
    <div style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:10px;color:var(--text3);text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;margin-bottom:12px">RNN Unrolled Over Time</div>
    <div class="flow-row">
      <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">t=1</div><div class="flow-text">x₁ → h₁</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">t=2</div><div class="flow-text">x₂ + h₁ → h₂</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box"><div class="flow-label">t=3</div><div class="flow-text">x₃ + h₂ → h₃</div></div>
      <div class="flow-row-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-box highlight"><div class="flow-label">t=n</div><div class="flow-text">xₙ + hₙ₋₁ → output</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g2" style="margin-top:14px">
    <div class="card card-rose">
      <div class="card-title ct-rose">Vanishing Gradient Problem</div>
      <p>In long sequences, gradients shrink exponentially as they travel backward through time steps. After ~10 steps, early information is effectively "forgotten".</p>
      <p>🌊 <em>Like a photocopy of a photocopy of a photocopy — each step loses fidelity until the original is unrecognizable.</em></p>
      <p>This is why vanilla RNNs fail at long-range dependencies (translating a 100-word sentence).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-lime">
      <div class="card-title ct-lime">LSTM — Long Short-Term Memory (1997)</div>
      <p>Adds explicit memory cell (Cₜ) controlled by three gates:</p>
      <ul class="bl lime">
        <li><strong>Forget Gate:</strong> What to erase from memory</li>
        <li><strong>Input Gate:</strong> What new info to store</li>
        <li><strong>Output Gate:</strong> What to use for output</li>
      </ul>
      <p>🔒 <em>Like a notebook with selective erasure — write what's important, erase what's not.</em></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout c-gold">
    <div class="c-icon">⚡</div>
    <div class="c-body">
      <strong>Why Transformers Replaced RNNs</strong>
      RNNs/LSTMs process tokens sequentially — cannot parallelize. Training a 1000-token sequence requires 1000 sequential steps. Transformers process ALL tokens simultaneously using attention — 1 step regardless of sequence length. This parallelism enabled training on internet-scale data.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- TRANSFORMERS — THE CROWN JEWEL -->
<section class="section" id="transformer">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div class="sec-icon si-gold">⚡</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <div class="sec-tag">Chapter 4.4 — Critical Deep Dive</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Transformers — The Architecture That Changed AI Forever</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout c-gold">
    <div class="c-icon">📜</div>
    <div class="c-body">
      <strong>"Attention Is All You Need" — Vaswani et al., 2017</strong>
      One paper eliminated recurrence entirely and introduced self-attention as the primary mechanism. This single architectural decision unlocked GPT, BERT, Claude, Gemini, and virtually all modern AI systems. Understanding transformers = understanding modern AI.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-gold">
    <div class="card-title ct-gold">The Core Intuition: Attention</div>
    <p>When you read "The animal didn't cross the street because <strong>it</strong> was too tired" — your brain instantly knows "it" refers to "animal" not "street". This requires understanding relationships between words regardless of their distance in the sequence.</p>
    <p>Attention allows every word to directly look at every other word and decide: <em>"How much should I pay attention to that word when building my representation?"</em></p>
