  <div class="card card-gold">
    <div class="card-title ct-gold">Self-Attention Deep Dive — Query, Key, Value</div>
    <p>🔑 <em>Analogy:</em> Think of a <strong>library search system</strong>. Your search query is Q. Each book's title/topic is a K. The actual book content is V.</p>
    <p>You compute similarity between your Q and every K. Books with titles matching your query (high similarity) contribute more of their content V to your answer. Books with irrelevant titles contribute almost nothing.</p>
    <div class="code"><span class="cm"># Self-Attention — step by step</span>
<span class="cm"># 1. Project input X into Q, K, V matrices</span>
Q = X @ W_Q  <span class="cm"># What am I looking for?</span>
K = X @ W_K  <span class="cm"># What do I contain?</span>
V = X @ W_V  <span class="cm"># What is my actual information?</span>

<span class="cm"># 2. Compute attention scores (how much to attend)</span>
scores = Q @ K.transpose(-<span class="num">2</span>, -<span class="num">1</span>) / math.sqrt(d_k)

<span class="cm"># 3. Apply causal mask (decoder only — no future peeking)</span>
scores = scores.masked_fill(mask == <span class="num">0</span>, float(<span class="str">'-inf'</span>))

<span class="cm"># 4. Softmax → attention weights (sum to 1)</span>
attention_weights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-<span class="num">1</span>)

<span class="cm"># 5. Weighted sum of values</span>
output = attention_weights @ V</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-cyan">
    <div class="card-title ct-cyan">Multi-Head Attention — Why Multiple Heads?</div>
    <p>One attention head might focus on grammatical relationships (verb-subject agreement). Another might focus on coreference (pronoun-noun linking). A third might focus on semantic similarity.</p>
    <p><strong>Multi-head attention runs H parallel attention heads simultaneously</strong>, each learning different relationship types. Results are concatenated and projected.</p>
    <div class="code"><span class="cm"># Multi-Head Attention in PyTorch</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="cls">MultiHeadAttention</span>(nn.Module):
    <span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">__init__</span>(<span class="hl">self</span>, d_model=<span class="num">512</span>, n_heads=<span class="num">8</span>):
        d_k = d_model // n_heads  <span class="cm"># 64 per head</span>
        <span class="hl">self</span>.heads = nn.<span class="fn">ModuleList</span>([AttentionHead(d_k) <span class="kw">for</span> _ <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(n_heads)])
        <span class="hl">self</span>.W_o = nn.<span class="fn">Linear</span>(d_model, d_model)

    <span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">forward</span>(<span class="hl">self</span>, x):
        head_outputs = [h(x) <span class="kw">for</span> h <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="hl">self</span>.heads]
        concat = torch.<span class="fn">cat</span>(head_outputs, dim=-<span class="num">1</span>)
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="hl">self</span>.W_o(concat)</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-violet">
    <div class="card-title ct-violet">Positional Encoding — Teaching Order to Attention</div>
    <p>Attention is <strong>order-invariant</strong> by default — "dog bites man" and "man bites dog" look the same to pure attention. We need to inject position information.</p>
    <p>Positional encoding adds a unique vector to each token's embedding based on its position, using sine and cosine functions at different frequencies. The model can then attend to both content and position.</p>
    <div class="formula-eq" style="font-family:var(--fm);font-size:12px;color:var(--cyan);background:rgba(0,229,255,.05);border:1px solid rgba(0,229,255,.15);border-radius:8px;padding:10px 16px;margin:10px 0">PE(pos, 2i) = sin(pos / 10000^(2i/dmodel)) &nbsp;·&nbsp; PE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(pos / 10000^(2i/dmodel))</div>
  </div>

  <div class="g2">
    <div class="card card-rose">
      <div class="card-title ct-rose">Why Transformers Changed AI Forever</div>
      <ul class="bl rose">
        <li><strong>Parallelizable:</strong> Process all tokens at once (vs sequential RNNs)</li>
        <li><strong>Long-range dependencies:</strong> Every token attends to every other token directly</li>
        <li><strong>Scalable:</strong> More data + bigger model = better performance (scaling laws)</li>
        <li><strong>Versatile:</strong> Works for text, images (ViT), audio, protein sequences, code</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-lime">
      <div class="card-title ct-lime">Transformer Variants</div>
      <ul class="bl lime">
        <li><strong>Encoder-only (BERT):</strong> Understanding tasks (classification, NER)</li>
        <li><strong>Decoder-only (GPT, LLaMA):</strong> Generation tasks (text, code)</li>
        <li><strong>Encoder-Decoder (T5, BART):</strong> Seq-to-seq (translation, summarization)</li>
        <li><strong>Vision Transformer (ViT):</strong> Images split into patches, treated as tokens</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

