<!-- INTERVIEW PREP -->
<section class="section" id="interview">
  <div class="section-head">
    <div class="sec-icon si-rose">📋</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <div class="sec-tag">Interview Preparation</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Top Interview Questions + Answers</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-list">
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">What is the difference between self-attention and cross-attention?</div>
      <div class="iq-a">Self-attention: Q, K, V all come from the same sequence (token attending to other tokens in same sequence). Cross-attention: Q from decoder, but K and V come from encoder output — lets the decoder attend to the full encoded input.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">Why does transformer attention scale by √dₖ?</div>
      <div class="iq-a">For large dₖ (key dimension), the dot products QKᵀ grow large in magnitude. Softmax of very large values produces near-one-hot distributions (peaked), causing vanishing gradients. Dividing by √dₖ keeps dot products in a reasonable range for stable softmax gradients.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">What is the difference between RAG and fine-tuning? When to use each?</div>
      <div class="iq-a">RAG: retrieve external knowledge at inference time. No training needed. Good for frequently changing data, citations needed, private documents. Fine-tuning: bake knowledge into weights via training. Good for style/format adaptation, domain-specific reasoning patterns, no latency budget for retrieval. Most enterprise systems use BOTH.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">Explain the vanishing gradient problem and how LSTM solves it.</div>
      <div class="iq-a">In vanilla RNNs, gradients are multiplied by the same weight matrix at each timestep. For long sequences (100+ steps), gradients shrink exponentially to near-zero (vanish) or grow explosively. LSTMs use a dedicated cell state (Cₜ) with additive updates (not multiplicative) controlled by gates — gradients can flow through the cell state highway without degrading.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">What is LoRA and why is it parameter-efficient?</div>
      <div class="iq-a">LoRA decomposes weight updates ΔW into two low-rank matrices A (d×r) and B (r×d), where r << d. Instead of training all d² parameters of ΔW, we only train d×r + r×d = 2dr parameters. For a 4096×4096 attention matrix with r=16, that's 4096×4096=16.7M vs 2×4096×16=131K — 127× fewer params.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">What is hallucination in LLMs and how do you mitigate it?</div>
      <div class="iq-a">LLMs generate statistically likely sequences, not factually guaranteed ones. They can confidently state false information. Mitigations: RAG (ground in real documents), temperature=0 for factual tasks, citation-required prompting, fact-checking pipelines, smaller specialized models (less interpolation between irrelevant training data), Constitutional AI training.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">What is the difference between BERT and GPT architectures?</div>
      <div class="iq-a">BERT: encoder-only, bidirectional attention (each token attends to all other tokens). Pre-trained with masked language modeling. Best for understanding tasks (classification, NER, QA). GPT: decoder-only, causal (left-to-right) attention with causal mask. Pre-trained with next-token prediction. Best for generation tasks (text, code, conversation).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="iq">
      <div class="iq-q">How does PagedAttention in vLLM improve throughput?</div>
      <div class="iq-a">Traditional LLM serving pre-allocates contiguous KV cache memory for max sequence length — most of it wasted for shorter sequences. PagedAttention borrows from OS virtual memory: KV cache is stored in non-contiguous pages, allocated on demand. Eliminates fragmentation, enables 2-4× more concurrent requests on same GPU.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

